\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid5850145 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
If I could ask you when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname date}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Year}{\xmlattrvalue 1889}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Day}
{\xmlattrvalue 24}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Month}{\xmlattrvalue 9}}}September 24}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , 1889{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 (1887)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, 1889.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 (I'm 1897)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And whereabouts were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 Walkworth New Farm, about quarter of a mile from here.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And what was your father's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He was farm labourer, then - then he became, when he shifted to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 Borwick}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , he was farm bailiff. What they call a shepherd and steward you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It was a step up that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did you have a cottage that went with the job when you were down this way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How large was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 The farm?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 The cottage which you had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh the cottage was just a small, two rooms, two bedrooms and a kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, a lovely garden, yes, yes. Plenty of garden. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 A vegetable garden had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Vegetables, yes. And we got, you got a ton of potatoes from the farm every year. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you milk from them as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well we had to buy the milk. Yes. When we were with New Barnes we had to buy our own milk but after we went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 Borwick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , the cows were milked, the milk was taken to the
 farmer, to the gentleman farmer you see, they took the cream off, and what milk came back to the cottages, was free milk, all free milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Skimmed milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Skimmed milk yes. You got as much as ever you wanted. And then we would feed, we had that muc
h surplus milk we fed perhaps two pigs in the year. Cured our own bacon. I have seen two pigs hanging on the ceiling! Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many brothers and sisters had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Three brothers and four sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 A large family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And my father had only, he only had about twenty-one shilling a week. He brought seven of us up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How did your mother make ends meet do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well we were much happier then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 In what sort of way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well things were much more cheaper then you know.
 And then you had your own bacon, you had your milk, you see, and your potatoes on the farm, you need never buy potatoes you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you hens as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, we hadn't hens. The farmer had you know. And we could get, we got always eggs cheaper, o
n the farm. But Mother used to look after the poultry. Yes. And we had, we were pretty well off then you know. Yes. And I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 went;}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  we walked to school from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 Borwick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  school that is four miles. Four miles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How old were you when you moved up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Eleven years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 
And then we walked there, down by Warkworth Station you know right down. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Thought nothing at it, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How about your mid-day meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh we'd carry it. Sandwiches.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would you have in sandwiches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Meat sandwich, or some
times pie you know, with a crust on it you know. And sometimes when there was fruit you have rhubarb and gooseberry tarts, that sort of thing, that's just what we used to carry. And then we had a good meal when we came home you know. Of course we never go
t far away you know, if we go the farthest we ever got was to Alnwick, we got the train at the Warkworth Station you see. You used to be at Alnwick, well the fare then was only 10d. return, now it is 1/10d. single.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, it has altered, hasn't it. How often actually would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh about once a month. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 For a market was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Yes. And then we had, the grocer came from Alnwick, and of course he used to come every month, to deliver the groceries you know. And the same with the flour miller. He used to bring about 20 stone of flour a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your mother must have done lot's of baking!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh she had to bake about 14, 15 loaves a week. She had these large tins you know, the dough full to the top!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of a kitchen had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh we had a good large kitchen. It was the old fashioned metal range you know. And big square oven you know. Oh yes. So we, we got on very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you a sink in your kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. And of course the water was outside, the tap outside the d
oor you know. But, er, things have changed greatly since then. All modernised now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well things were rather primitive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Ah yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It must have been a bit squashed, all those children and a small cottage -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. Yes. We only had two bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many beds were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
There were two in the large room and one in the little one, smaller room, and one downstairs. The kitchen, the very large kitchen see, and a recess, which used at one time was what was called the box bed, you were closed in. Sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 partitioned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your parents sleep there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Of course that had been pulled out before we went to Borwick because we had one of these old fashioned pole beds. The four pole bed you know, wood you know, and a canopy over the top.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I see. In the kitchen was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. You see at one time it must have been partitioned off. From the kitchen. But it was all opened out and you just put the bed back into that recess and you had room perhaps to
 put the sewing machine in it, at the end of the bed. Pretty roomy you know. Roomy kitchen. And then when I went, I went to Eastfield, fifteen years there in the gardens. And then we had the horses and carriages there you know. When I was seventeen I was 
riding in livery. Silk hat and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How superb.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And you livery was all made you know. Silver buttons. And these gaiters, you know, with four buttons up the gaiters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How old were you when you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Fourteen. I left school on the Friday night and I was working on the Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I suppose your parents needed -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Yes, you see, I was the oldest you see. Now me second brother, he did the same. But the third brother got the higher education. Yes, he won a scholarship.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Where did he go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
He went to the Alnwick Duke's School. Then after he finished schooling he was Clerk to the Board of Guardians at Alnwick. Then he got on as rate collector. Then he went on to the Ashington, and he had four clerks under him there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your parents were interested in education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
We used to often kid him about us having to work to school him!! But he is dead. He just died last year. But he had, he was very clever. Grand scholar you know. Shorthand writing and everything. Of course we never had that privilege.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you any books or newspapers in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Er, we used to get one, one a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 The Alnwick Gazette. That was all we had. No Sunday papers. We weren't allowed, on a Sunday we wer
en't allowed out. Playing. Go to Sunday School and in the afternoon get a book and read. We weren't allowed to gad about outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of books would you read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh, good reading books you know, school books, and that sort of thing you know. 
But you weren't allowed, on a Sunday, nothing to do, weren't allowed to do anything on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were your parents strict with you in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. We went to Sunday School every Sunday morning and we stayed, Mother would come down to the Church at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 11}}}eleven o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 you see and we would stay at the Church as well. And then after we finished Sunday School we went with her to the Church you see. I've never been, it has never left me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How about your father - did he go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, oh yes, he was a
n Elder. And I was an Elder before he died. Father and son was Elder. I think twenty-three years an Elder and about thirty years on the Board of Management. Mr. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12134120\charrsid14627296 Adgerson}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , he was the first Minister, he baptised me. Revere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 d William Rogerson. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I have heard his name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, and then we had Mr. Gardener. Mr. Richey. Mr. Lawrence. Mr. Mead. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
Mr. Dye, Mr. Freeds(?) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 - the seventh. I have been under seven. And I have seen that Church go from, we were pretty low water at one time, at one time we just had about three Elders you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh it was as small as that!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Yes. And there was one Elder, he was both Clerk to the Management and Clerk to the Session you see. Well it was too much for one to do. Well they called a meeting of the Session and there
 was only three of us there. Elders, and the Minister, one was a retired Policeman, so we proposed he be elected us Session Clerk, and he flatly refused. Well he turned round and proposed me! You see, and it was seconded, well what could I do? So the Mini
s
ter said to me, he says "You will not turn it down, will you?" I said No. I said I never left a sinking ship!" Of course we were pretty low water at the time, and since then it has gone from strength to strength. Yes. And of course we have had a lot of fa
ithful men and women that have gone you know, before, used to be strong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was Warkworth pretty strong Presbyterian?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you any other Church activities On weeknights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Er we have, well in the earlier days, younger days, we 
had a literary society, debating society. And Mr. Rogerson used to take the debating society. It used to be up in the gallery of the Church. We had no hall then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many people would there be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh about fourteen or fifteen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Quite a lot isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. And there used to be a Band of Hope, these bits of things. But there is more attraction now than there used to be then. Far more attraction for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would you do with your evenings? Spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh we would just potter about the garden, amuse ourselves you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you a musical family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I have heard of people having musical evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Mind we used to, there was a family living next door, used to be great dancers, and musicians. They could p
lay any instrument. We used to made of wood and step dancing, oh step dancing hard wood maybe knock some boots off you know! Oh there was a melodian and fiddles. Oh we used to have some, and every year the farmer gave us a corn supper after the harvest yo
u know. In the granary. We used to have a supper and dance you know. Dance the whole night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And all his workers would go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. Then we would perhaps invite some of the other farms round about you know. All the farms used to have this cor
n supper every year. And we were always invited to them you see. Usually after the last harvest was in you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did anything special happen at Christmas time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No. There wasn't much at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 New Year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. We used to go round the
 farms you know. Oh yes, we had some very happy times. When I left Eastfield no I was at Borwick. Then the war broke out, the First war, and I left my job and joined the Army and I was four year, three year and four months away. And I remember we went to 
S
alonica. And joined the Serbian Army, we were attached, the British Company attached to the Serbian Army. They had lost all their country, they were lying on the Greek Frontier, you know. And we went to their assistance. And we stayed with them until they
 
got the country back. And I got attached to the driver, for mechanical transport you see. And I was attached to the Crown Prince. To bring his rations up to his dugout, he was with his troops at the front line. And I used to have to run his rations from t
he rail head every day. And I got attached to the headquarters staff after we finished with the Serbian Army. Then headquarters shifted to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Constantinople{\*\xmlclose}
, went to the Sultan's Palace. Billeted in there. Yes. And I got, I got leave from there and I was supposed to go back there, I had to sign a paper saying I would go back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Constantinople{\*\xmlclose}
, I said once I get over that pond. I won't be back. And I got a cablegram, I had me month's leave and I should have gone straight from leave to me depot, and reported at m
e depot, but I come straight home and nobody knew I was here. And I had to go and get, I wrote to headquarters in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grove{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, for instructions where to report. I got the reply "Report Grove Park Depot forthwith" so when I got there, they were putti
ng civilian girls into the offices, you know, to relieve the men, and I went to this office you know and there was a girl sitting there in civvies. She says }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Name and number?" So I gave her me name you know and she said "Where have you been?" "Aye," I said
 "I am not going to say where I have been" I was beginning to get a bit cautious you know. "Well", she said "For your own good I'm asking you" "Oh" I said "if you have any good in your mind let's have it", she says "I made your demobilisation papers }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 ut a 
month ago." You see if I had reported at the depot, I'd been sent for them, and my papers would have come through you see. I said "Where are they now then" she said "{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Constantinople{\*\xmlclose}!"
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 "Oh" she said "you will be confined to camp
 until your papers come through". So the next morning, I went to the parade you know. I went out on parade. And er, they pulled me out for dental treatment. And I got into the chair you know, and the officer that was drawing teeth, you know, the dental of
ficer "Ah" he says "have you joined up again?" "No" I said "I am awaiting demobilisation". "Well" he said "I advise you to get out of here because you've three months }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 et}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ". }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
So I jumped out of the chair and said "That's enough for me, I'm away!" Well when I 
got, he said "I will give you a line off my hand" and he said "you will get your teeth from the Ministry of Pensions". "Well" I said "I have eaten hard biscuits for three years and four months, so I shouldn't be too bad!"
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What happened after the War ended, did you settle down here again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
I came back to me old job. But the farmer, me boss, died when I was away. But the son was also a Captain in the Tyneside Scottish Regiment, he was demobbed, and he took over his father's business. And I went bac
k to him. And I had two year with him. And then I had a change, I went up to Eastfield, W.J.Sanderson. The founder of the Crippled Homes Gosforth and they were nice people. And I was with him until he died and then there was Atherson of Sunderland, ship b
u
ilders, bought Eastfield, and he died four months after he bought it. And his widow carried on for two years. We had lovely gardens there, oh the great lawn ranged the full length of the garden, and greenhouses. We had a peach house, a carnation house and
 two vineries, and a tomato house, oh we used to do great things even Warkworth Show, it is one of the oldest established shows. And we used to show extensively there. We once set out, there Challenge Cup, the most -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You said you worked on a farm when you first left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How did that happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 That was the neighbouring farm to Brotherwick it was called the South Side. Mr. Grey was the farmer. I had one year with him, you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well me father wouldn't let m
e come under him, you see, he thought I would be better with a stranger, under a strange man you see. And I had one year away from Brotherwick and then I came back under me father for one year you see and then I went along to the farmer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  you know George Sanderso}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
 and he kept, he had lovely gardens, and he kept a groom gardener you see, driving the horse and trap you know. And I did that for a good few years. And then we changed over to motors you see. And he put me away to a garage for a month to learn the 
motoring, and that's how we started the motoring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was he a good employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. Very strict, very particular you know, very tidy, he once asked me a question, when I started in the garden, he asked me to go into the garden and see what I could
 do. Well he said "Do you know the first thing to learn about the garden?" "Aye well I couldn't, I have never done much gardening". He said "Tidyness," he said, "that's the motto. And it's a good one too you know. Clean up as you go you know. You see some
 people just drop everything where they are, you know. Tools and that sort. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Tidiness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 . He was quite strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How much holidays did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 There was no holidays then. Oh no. No. It is only in the last twenty years you've got holidays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So you never got out of Warkworth really then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
Mr. Sanderson at Eastfield, I went to him, it was the Exhibition you know, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 he sent, there was the Head Gardener, there was the Chauffeur, there was meself, he sent the three families up for a week. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
He paid all the expenses - Cooks Tours you know. You never needed to put your hand in your pocket. Hotel fees and everything was already paid. And we had a week at Wembley. At the Exhibition. And then we had, we used got a weeks holiday after that we w
ent down to Seahouses or along to Eyemouth, Whitley Bay, or some of these places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How old were you when you first went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh I would be, well er Exhibition, 15 - I make it 301}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  I remember \{BLANK\} I had never been in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} before
. No more than going in the Army you see. I once landed there off the boat, on leave, and got on the platform at the station at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 14}}}2 o'clock{\*\xmlclose} in the morning. We didn't know where to go, do you know what we did? We went in the underground and of course we had a Railway }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 W}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
arrant you know and we went in the underground and we did a sort of, we landed right back where we started. Then Eastfield Hall was burnt down about eight or nine years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you a house on the-?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 On the grounds Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you always had a house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes, I never paid rent until I came to the Council house. When I went to Foxbury to Colonel Maxwell, we lived in part of the house, which used to be the maids quarters, the back stairs, and we lived in there and it was real nic
e because there was a door lead from our part into his part you see and he wouldn't allow me to lock it up. "No" he said "you are in my house and I'm in yours, we're all together!" That was the spirit. Now the people before that, they put a partition up b
e
tween their landing and ours, to make it more private you see. When Colonel Maxwell bought the place, I was showing him round and we came up to this partition and he said "What is the meaning of this piece of hardboard, what is the idea of this." "Well th
at is to separate the corn from the chaff!" and he said "I'm not having that, pull that out. You're in my house and I am in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 thine,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  yours". Do you know I weighed that man's character up straight away. He was a man I'd never seen before.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It sounds as though you have been awfully fortunate in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, very fortunate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I suppose you stayed at home until you were married did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. I was married in 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How did you meet your wife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She was housemaid at Borwick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And she was, she belonged {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 bell{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 (?)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you known her for a long while then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. I knew her before she came to Borwick. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
She used to be at Sturton Grange with the Fyles, Tom Fyles' father, that comes to Church and then we shifted from there, we were married when I was at Borwick I was about a year there after we were married and then I went to Eastfield.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was it quite easy changing jobs round then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well Captain Tate you know, he wasn't the same chap as his father. And I was with 
the father, because when I left and said goodbye to the father and I went to join the Army he said "Yes, he said I'm on borrowed days you've a lifetime to look forward to" and he was dead right at that. And when I left him, I had ten gold sovereigns in me
 
pocket, so I gave him the ten gold sovereigns to keep for me, you see, until I came back, there were no use to me in the Army. So when I came back of course he was dead, and I didn't know where those ten gold sovereigns were you know. They had an accounta
n
t used to come from Alnwick, to do his books you know and a month or two after I returned, I went into Alnwick one day and I knew where the accountant lived and he was just standing at his door and he saw me along the High Street you know, and he called m
e back. And he says "I have got ten gold sovereigns belonging to you"!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How had you saved up so much? That was quite a lot!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh well, living in do you see. You had all your food. Oh yes. You lived on the best. They had a cook there, she died with t
hat family, she had fifty years service with them one house. And she was a lovely cook. And she was like a mother to me when I first went there, as a young lad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You were only fifteen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, yes. And she was like a mother to me. You slept in the 
house, you had your room, your livery to look after and all that you know. Of course you didn't, there was nowhere to spend it anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How much were your wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Oh we were getting about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8156036 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 2 per week then.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 That wasn't bad was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, that was good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did you see your parents very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. We had Sabbath afternoon you know, Sunday. Except every other week, you see there had to be a duty man for the gardens you see. We had to do the watering you know, and the heating, looking
 after the heating of the greenhouses. Well there was two of us you see, one did one weekend and the other the other. Every other weekend we had off. Oh yes, I've enjoyed it. The outdoor life you know. And I have been blessed with good health. I have neve
r lost a day through illness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How long was your day - it sounds quite a big establishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Seven in the morning, 'till five. An hour for lunch. And your tea when you finished at five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 The same in winter was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Still the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How large a staff was there there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
They'd be about - altogether we'd ten staff in that establishment. Round about five maids in the house and three out - two men and a boy in the gardens. A laundry maid, did all the laundry, a special laundry built you
 know, drying rooms and everything. And that was when all these young ladies you know, played tennis you know, all in that white - everything was white you know. There was some washing in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you tennis courts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. There was a lovely lodge you see, and I lived in the lodge, at the entrance gate, lovely lodge on the flat. And, er, .... }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 But Foxbury,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14627296  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Foxbury was a different.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You said your mother had a sewing machine - and she made your own clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, made our clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Where actually would she buy her fabric from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 From an old firm in Alnwick called pit. And the shop is still there yet. And the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 traveller}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  used to come round once a month you know to get the orders. Oh she made everything. An old Treadle machine, t
he old singer machine, stood on a stand you now. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She must have been a very busy woman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. Hard working yes. And then she looked after the poultry. Milked the cows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was she paid for that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. That was a little extra you 
know. And then she had to carry the milk about 300 yards. But all, except the brother that died, we are all living, there is one living, my brother lives at High Buston, and of course he has retired of course. But he is not fit to do anything - heart trou
ble. And then me brother at High }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Buston,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
 well Mr Nelson and I take Communion once a quarter you see, for the aged people that can't come to Church, we go out and give them Communion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How old were you when you started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Five. Yes, that time you see we had to work. Well you couldn't go much earlier than five, the distance you had to go to school. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 How far, well to Walworth New Barns it is about oh a mile and a quarter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Then when we went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Borwick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  it was four miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How large a school was it? How many teachers were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Three - one, two, three - and the headmaster. There was more children there than what there is now. For all this extra building you know, round about, but mostly older people, lot of old people buy these houses you s
ee. Well sort of business people retired you know. And the young people, want to leave school, have to go where the college and that sort of thing you know. There's not the jobs here for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of jobs were available in your young days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well they worked on the farm then you know, the girls too. The, at Borwick there was four, wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 se th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
 you know, scarf you know there is none employed now you know, no girls employed, unless it is in the dairy, the dairy farm might employ one or two. Washi
ng milk dishes and that. But oh in those days it was a sight. There was one farm, the side of the station at Shortridge, I have seen eight girls working on the land. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 They went into domestic service as well didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. And that's all,
 a lot of that has been done away with. These big establishments are finished. Well that place now, Eastfield, well they employed ten people well there is nobody there now. So that goes on right way up the country you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 There is no industry here at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Nothing but the mines you know, miners, Shilbottle Broomhill which is closed, Foxlift which is closed, that's two collieries closed down. But there's Shilbottle going, that is about five mile away. That is the nearest. Well a lot of people now 
go to Alnwick. You know the shops, Woolworths and such places, there is employment there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were your school teachers local people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, all local. Yes, they were all people, there was a Miss Miller, she's dead. There was a Miss Grey which still lives in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Barnes Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh - she must be getting on!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She is. I did her garden last year for her. Yes. She's a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 marvellous}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did you enjoy school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. The only thing, you know, for the last two year of my schooling, the schoolmas
ter left, we got a new schoolmaster, and he seemed to upset everything. He changed all the methods you know. What sort of things? Handwriting and all that, he altered everything. And this was a sort of break in your schooling. Of course Briggs, the man I 
started with, was a real country schoolmaster. The next one we got, we was from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Quite different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. Town ideas you see. Whereas the other had the country ideas, and it seemed to upset everything. But I'd only two year with him. But 
I went right out all the standards out to X7 Standard, passed right out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Which were your favourite subjects?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh er Geography was mine. And I remarked that, I says "it is rather funny I was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Greece{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, er {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Greece{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Serbia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Albania{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Constantin - er {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Turkey{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
" and I said "I have been in five different countries and I have never seen any one better than this one!"
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh well that is good isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Just in building you know, in the building. You see at one time, when I was going to school
, I could start at the bottom of the Walkworth Street and I could tell you who lived in each house up that side and down the next. I couldn't now. Everything always changing you know. And that, where the garage is in the centre of the village, that used t
o be a brewery, a brewery yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 And rather funny, I go to a garden up on Heather Lacy Lees, she was a Miss Lamb and her father was the brewer. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And she is still living, the daughter. She's been out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 she married an Army Colonel or Captain or something and they were a long time in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But she's back in Warkworth. And she has another sister lives in Warkworth. Top of the Street. So that's the old Lamb family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It sounds as though it was a neighbourly area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well yes. It used to be amusing whe
n these burgess burgess/burghers people, each kept a cow you know. And it had to come through the passage you know, the bytes (?) were at the back of the house and there was no back road and they had to come through the passage you know. And you would see
 them when they were going out every day and you would see them going behind them with the shovel you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 They went home every day and came back in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, in case they did a mess in the passage! That's all done away with. They wouldn't allow it now you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you a cow ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
No. Me father had a cow kept, but not before I left home. He had one after I left. He was allowed a cow at one or two places. He went to he was in three different farms after that, and he was allowed a cow for himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He moved round a fair bit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, I used to, when I was in Borwick, I lived at the farmhouse you know, I lived in, well I used to go home every night, about ten o'clock and me father busy, you know, ewes to
 lamb and that sort of thing, he used to be out about 3 o'clock in the morning, so I went along about ten o'clock at night. He'd be away to bed, because he had to be up at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}
{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 15}}}three o'clock{\*\xmlclose}. And I used to go home at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}ten o'clock{\*\xmlclose} and loop look the sheep for him 
you know to save him getting up. Oh I used to help him out. I was interested in it you see. Been brought up on the farm you know. It came all naturally to you. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
I remember once he sent me round, they were expecting a cow, calvng you know, he sent me round, he said "Go and look to this cow, see if they are all right" so I went and all three cows were lying comfortable down for the night you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And I came back and he said "What were they like?" I said "They are all right, they are all lying comfortable, I d
idn't disturb them" and he said "which one did you look at" and I said "the whole lot, the three of them". A shepherd's life was pretty tiring especially at that time of year. You know. You see where there was stock, they need attention.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You didn't have much spare time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No spare time! Seven days a week you know. My sister's been on the farm an' all you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I can't understand how you parents managed with such a large family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well, it was easier like in those days than what it is
 now. Why? Well you had more perquisites you know, you had more from the farms you know. And I think one just brought up another!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You think it happened like that do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes. You had to look after each other! Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 My sister stayed with my father 'till he died you see. Kept his house for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How old would he have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 84. My misses died twelve year ago. When we were at Foxbury. We worked pretty well together in any social event you know the 
two churches go well together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Has it always been like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Not always. No. The Reverend James Fairbrother, when I was going to school, he was the vicar and he left and Canon Annan followed him. And so followed him and Bishop Dickenson and the present new one, Fox.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 They haven't always been friendly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
No, no. Bishop Dickenson was the funniest man. And we had a little trouble with him. Mr. Lawrence was the Presbyterian Minister then and he was going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} one day with that 28 bus you know and when he got into the bus Bishop Dickenson was sitting you know and he thought he would sit down with him to have his company to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City
}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. When he sat down the Bishop got up and went to another sea. So he called a meeting of the Session. He sa
id - I have been grossly insulted by the Bishop!" so the Bishop, at the Session Meeting it was discussed you know. Me being Session Clerk I had to write a letter and ask for an apology you see, well I got into bad books! So the next time we met, we were a
t a social evening at the public house (?) and I was talking to a chap, who was an Anglican member and Bishop Dickenson come forward and he started to introduce to Bishop Dickenson you know, and when he mentioned my name he made off! A very peculiar man. 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Do you he once, at Eastfield we had a new Second Man, Under gardener came from New Begin and Bishop Dickenson came up to visit him you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 A new member. And we were clipping a hedge on the road side I was at the top end and the other men was further down a
nd he met the other man first, the new man and he said to him "Who is the gentleman further up the road." "Well that's Mr. Darling" so he said "He is not of my Clock!" But mind, there has only been the one really good pageant. Because it takes a lot of mo
ney to stage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How long since was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 That will be about twenty year ago. We had a pageant, (to his sister) when we had a river pageant. The pageant on the river.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you any fairs round here at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 There used to be a fair held in the market place. Every November.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh, what sort of fair was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Stalls you know and cart loads of pigs for sale. Just a real country fair you know. And Warkworth Feast used to be a great do. That's the 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , it always fell on the Sunday nearest the 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
 August. That's when the flower show is held. It's the Feast of St. Lawrence, you see that was the Church of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}St.{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Lawrence
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and the Feast was fixed by the Church. And Warkworth Flower Show is kept that date. Every year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What happens on Warkworth Feast Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
The usual side shows came in, the roundabouts you know, that sort of thing, in the market place you know. But now its, all that there is now is just the Flower Show, there is nothing like that in the Market place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you any Sunday School outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. We used to go in farm carts at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 There to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
We used to, some of the farmers round about used to invite us, to a party you know. And they used to send the horses and carts. We had a photograph once - do you r
emember when we used to go to Stourton Grange - we had a photograph, the Sunday School outing at Stourton Grange?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 (Oh yes)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It showed you the group, you know, Sunday School Group. They still go White House \{ILLEGIBLE\} this year. \{BLANK\} went with
 them when Mr. Ryder was Minister, we were taking them to Spi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 tal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
 and he asked me to go with them and I went. What a job we had! We went through Berwick you know and we lost the half of them! You know they kept d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ragging}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  into the shops you know!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I can imagine!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I remember, we had to go over on the ferry, to Spit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 al}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  you know. Once we got them onto Spit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 al}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 ands you know we were all right, we had them all together, we had sports you know. But coming back it was the same old game, coming through Berwick
 Streets you know. It was just two of us \{BLANK\}
 course they knew what time they had to leave you know. At the station. I remember when we got to Warkworth Station that night he said "I'm glad, I'm glad you were with us. Never more will I take them back!" 
It was a responsibility you know. That is why they just take them locally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It is much safer isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Do any fishing boats go out from Warworth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No that's been stopped about ten years. Yes, there was net fishing. They used to dra
w the net. You know that, just below the old bridge, there used to be a very deep pool there, it was sort of washed out you know, and I've seen them cast the net in there and get about 50 salmon out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 And we used to fish right up the Coquet right up high up the Coquet. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
They had one boat fishing down below the falls, the dam you know, and they kept another boat above the damn, to fish the upper reaches. And I had an uncle who was on the fishing boat. There used to be four men to a boat you know. Of course the
y soon took all the salmon out of the river with the net you know! They got everything. Yes, the rod fishers didn't get many. There is no net fishing now. The Duke, you see they had to pay so much to the Duke of Northumberland for fishing the river. And h
e got to know how many fish they got, he used to guess, because the fisherman instead of sending all the fish to Warkworth Station, he sent some to Acklington and you see the Duke would get the receipt from Warkworth!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So they fiddled it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You know a village like Warkworth, there's been some rare characters in it, oh yes, some real old characters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 The sort of people that, I know one chap he was a joiner, supposed to be, he never did a days work in his life. He used t
o call himself a pulling down joiner!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What did that mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Full things to pieces not make them! There was a John Bell, he had been a policeman, he got the sack from that, he went as railroad guard, on the railway, and he forgot to put a perambula
tor out at a certain Station, and he shoved it out onto the railway side afore he got to the next station and he got the sack there! He was an awful chap! I remember one day, on the Amble Road there, it was at where the dam is across you know, on the rive
r, that didn't used to be there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
There was a chap with a roller, a steam roller, on the road, and this particular joiner came along, and he'd been the worse for drink you know and this chap with the roller said "Tom, you daresn't go into the river there and
 pull one of those salmon out by the gills and walk down Warkworth Street with it!" }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And he went and did it you know! In broad daylight, he walked down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Warkworth Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and there was never anybody said "Where did you get it." Had he done it in the dark he'd have been caught. But he did it that openly you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many shops were there in Warkworth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
There used to be one, two, three, four. There used to be four. Now there are one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, there would be eight now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of shops were they before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Four were grocers and two were butchers. There used to be three butchers at one time. That, there have been two shops opened out in the market place there. They've been opened out these last few years. The 
Warkworth House Hotel hasn't been that long in Warkworth you know, you know the Warkworth House Hotel. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 That used to be Glendenning, the wine merchants, Glendennings wine, he lived in there. 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 travelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  every morning to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} by train and George Thomps
on had the Walter Wilson's shop. And George Thompson, he was a bit of a character too. He put up a large sign, Wills' Golden Yellow Sign you know, Wills' Golden Flake tobacco you know, he had this sign outside. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Glendenning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  complained about this sign, disfi
guring the village so George Thompson got one back on him. He said "The last time I was on Edinburgh Railway Station, he said I couldn't get down the platform for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Glendenning's}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  beef (?) and mulled wine!" he says "so can you pull them down? I'm not pulling 
this one!" Oh they were great rivals you know. Just the one old sign. And then the Bridgend House next to the Tower (?) that used to be an old gentleman, an old country gentleman, Clutterbuck. He lived many years there. A chap about \{BLANK\}
 twenty four stone. They had to put double doors to get him out you know
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Now one of the things I was going to ask you was, you were born in Warkworth New Barnes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Warkworth New Barnes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of a house was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Two, three roomed cottage. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Three rooms upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Two bedrooms, living room and scullery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I see. And you lived there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Until I was eleven years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Until you were eleven, and you moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I moved to Brotherwick. Yes. And I was fifteen years there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was it a bigger house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes. Same number of rooms but larger yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And you also told me that you had three sisters and?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Three sisters and four brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of, well where did you come in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I was second oldest, I have a sister older than me, two years older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How much younger than you was the youngest one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would be about ten years, that's the youngest one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of jobs did your brothers go on to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I went onto the far
m for one year, and then I went into gardens the second year, and I've been in them ever since. And me other brothers worked on the farm, me third brother he went to Alnwick, the Registrar Office, and he was also rate collector, and then he went to Ashing
t
on, he was a leaven officer, he had four clerks there. And then he, he left that, and he went into the Police Force, clerking for the Police. Four was in the office and four on duty you see. But he is dead, he died two year ago, but we are all living exce
pt him, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about your fourth brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
He was on the farm too, but of course he has retired now as well. Now me youngest brother, he has just retired from the Rural District Council at Alnwick, after nineteen years with the Council, he has just retired this week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Me sisters, they are all married. There is one at \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 she married Mr. Dixon, one of the fishermen. And another sister at Duxford New Houses, her husband had to leave the farm, he got injur
ed, fell off a load and got injured in the back, he gets about all right, but, he goes into Alnwick for this basket working, \{ILLEGIBLE\} you know. And of course my younger brother, me other sister lives at \{IILEGIBLE\}
 she is still living, she is eighty-one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your sisters were all in service after they left school were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Have you any idea how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Seventy - oh me father he would be - he would be in his thirties. Yes, he was just, he was j
ust a farm labourer at the New Barns when I was born and when he went to Brotherwick he was a farm bailiff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And he worked as a bailiff all the rest of his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, yes. And me sister, that lives with me, she kept me father's house, 'till he di
ed and then I lost my missus about eleven year ago, so I asked her to give up the farm work, she was just killing herself you know, feeding cattle and that sort of thing, so I said come to me for a room and she has been with us ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about your mother? Was she the same age as your father do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, about the same age. And she died at the age of 77 I think, 77 yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And what had she done before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I think she would be on the farm as well. They had a lot o
f women workers then you know, on the farms. It is rather funny you know, on the Church Register Mother Mother's name is on there, baptised there, and all the family were baptised in the same church and they are not on the Register. Well we looked it up, 
and the Minister that was there then, he had let the Register go you know, for so many years, it is a shame you know, he had let it go like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Now, one of the other things was would your mother have a specific day for doing specific things 
in the house, like would she always do the washing on the same day -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, the washing and baking. She did all her own baking you know, bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When were her baking days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Generally about Thursday I think, about a Thursday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She would bake on a Thursday
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Wash on a Monday perhaps. We used to get 20 stone of flour in at a time. They buy it by the pound now!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Who made your shoes or?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 We wore all bought, ready made you know, but me father he got his, me father had his special
ly made, hand made, to stand the wet grass you know, in the stock and that you see. They had to be all hand sewn. And there was an old cobbler in Warkworth, Coulder (?) they called him, and he used to make them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your father ever help your mother with any jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well, he hadn't much time, not when he had stock (?) you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would he ever make the fires or bring in coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh, yes, he always lit the fire. All the time that I knew. It is rather funny, the match that lit the fire lit his pipe every morning.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He wouldn't ever help with you small children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes, take them out you know. And when we were old enough we had to go to Church with him on a Sunday morning, we used to walk four miles. We were all brought up, right from
 children, to go to Sunday School, and you never forget it, No. That's the trouble today you know, they talk about reviving the churches you know, but I say the revival should be in the home, by the parents, that's where to start the revival.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your parents were very concerned about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. We weren't allowed to gallivant about on a Sunday you know. Oh know. You had to get a book and sit. Oh there was nothing done on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of books had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well school books you know and that sort. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your parents ever read books to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were there any jobs which you would always do and help your mother with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, well she had the, she had to milk the cows and the milk had to go to the fa
rmhouse every day and it was about, about three or four hundred yards to the house, and I used to carry the milk for her, do you see. Then I went to that farmhouse as gardener groom you know, and we had the horses and I started there, well I used to carry
 
the milk back and forward you see, and the milk that came, the new milk that came to the farmhouse in the morning, you took that back at night. You see. You brought the new, and after they take the cream off, and you brought the rest of the milk back to t
he farm cottages, and it was divided free amongst them. They got free milk. As much as ever you could use. It was a great help you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were there any other jobs that your brothers and sisters did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Two sisters went into service you know, privat
e service. And the other one used to be on the farm, until they were married. There used to be about four women working out on the farm. You see there is none now, it is all done away with that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you were still a child, did your older brothers and sisters help with the smaller ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, one seemed to bring the other one up! Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How would you manage about baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well you just had to get the tub in you know, bath you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 In the scullery or the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, yes. The scullery. You had to just make the best of it. I went to, I was fifteen years in the gardens at \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 then I went to Eastfield, it's not far off, Mr. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Sanderson's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
. I remember George Tate, he was the gentlemen at Brotherwick, but I was on with his fat
her before him. At the time I was in the Army the father died, and I took on with the son, which was a Captain Tate, and I remember when I went to Eastfield he said "Why don't you go to Mr. Sanderson, a man you know so well?" I said "That's the man I'm go
i
ng to!" Of course he wasn't, he hadn't a good name you see, Mr. Sanderson, he wondered why I went to. I said "That's the devil I'll go to, the one I know. And that worked out splendid. Just as though you'd take to people you see. Of course he was inclined
 
to suffer a bit from gout you know, and get out of temper sometimes you know. But I got on fine with him, I used to laugh at him you know, when he started bleating you know. He used to say "You get your money every week, and I can't get a suit of clothes 
to my back? I said "Oh," I says "if I had as much money as you I'd have a dozen suits". I was thirty-two years there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you were still a school boy, would all the family have their meals at the same time or would your father be away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well we just, you'd carry just a sandwich or something like that to school and you'd just got your tea when you come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of things would you have for your tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Just a plain tea you know. Perhaps a girdle (?) cake now and again. Of course whe
n there was seven of you, you know, you couldn't do with many luxuries you know, when there was seven, and the wages then was only about a pound a week you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your father have the same food as you or?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, yes, just the same, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you have meat once a week or more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh no. Of course you see we fed pigs you see. Plenty of ham, hanging up at the ceiling you know. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 when you wanted. So you were never short of meat. We'd get perhaps butcher's meat once a week you know. But through the week it was mostly cold ham, or cooked ham, hot. \{ILLEGIBLE\} Always plenty of bacon, eggs you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did your parents have any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, plenty of vegetables, but we hadn't much fruit about the gardens, mostly 
vegetables. And then you got, you got a ton of potatoes off the farm every year you see, which kept you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you allowed to speak at all at meal times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 They wouldn't mind if you talked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would happen if you left some food on your plate? Would your mother - \{ILLEGIBLE\}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, no, no. She wouldn't mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She wouldn't mind at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you ask if you wanted a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes. And you'd get it too. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your mother insist that you stayed at the table until all had finished the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, you'd ask, to leave the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would anybody say grace ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, oh yes. \{ILLEGIBLE\} Always me father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would he always say grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes. And he was on the session (?) at the Presbyterian Church and I was elected onto the session at the same time during the time that he was on the session. Father and son on the session, and I have been on it ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Asking about your mother, would you say that she was an easy sort of person to get on with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, we had a good mother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would she show affection for her children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. If she could afford it, you got whatever you asked for, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was your father much the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did your parents bring you up to behave in a certain way to your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, we always, we always, even after they were married and away, they still went and saw them you know. Now even o
n Saturday at me niece's wedding, we were all there. Both brothers and sisters and grandchildren, they were all there, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you say your parents brought you up to think of certain things as most important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, they did yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of things would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well you had to live up to the faith. And we were taught all the best that they could give us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were these ideas mostly from your mother or your father or both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 From them both, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would happen if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh we got told off you know. But I don't think any of us ever got, what you'd say, a good }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 thrashing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  you know, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Not at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was it your mother or your father that would punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Me father. Yes. M
e mother, she wouldn't lift a hand to you. No. No. And then we had an aunt stay, mother's oldest sister, she could never have her schooling, through illness, and she always stayed with us, and she took an awful interest in children you know, you mustn't l
ay a hand on any of them, she wouldn't allow you, on the younger ones you know, oh no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She used to live with you did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, well you see she, her health never would allow her to get her schooling you know. And she came to live with us and as 
we grew up you know we used to give her a shilling or anything like that you know, pocket money you know. And she knew the value of money, but she never had any schooling. She couldn't read or write, but she knew the value of money. Just by sight you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was she like an elder sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
She was mother's eldest sister yes. And she lived 'till she was 77 as well. And the longer she lived, the older she got the better health she got. And when she died, the doctor said he couldn't certify anything. Jus
t sort of senile decay. But she just lay there singing hymns. She could sing, and she sang hymns right up to when she died, night and day. Of course you see she knew she probably lived \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 that way you know, couldn't read or write well she never saw anything wrong you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would she help your mother with housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, oh yes. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 help. You hadn't to go and interfere if she was washing dishes or anything and you wanted to help, you hadn't to go near, she wouldn't allow you. Oh no, she didn't like you to take the job from her you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So she lived with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Up 'till she died, yes. Yes. And she just died about two years before Mother died. Mother always said she was glad that she had seen her away yes. She said she wouldn't have liked her to have lived after her you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of things }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 you all would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  do, the whole family when you had an evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, we'd chop the sticks, carrying the coals and feed the pigs. Oh yes. Helping in the garden you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When it was dark and you'd all finished work and you all sat down, what would you do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Reading books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And doing your homework from school. Yes. We got plenty of that in those days, in fact they nearly gave you as much homework as you got \{
ILLEGIBLE\} the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What were birthdays like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh just, there was always a girdle scone, and a sixpence in it. Yes, whose ever birthday it was. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 I remember me sister used to, me sister that is with me, she was wor
king out on the farm and it was her birthday. Well one of me younger brothers was at home at the time, and they went the tea out to the field you know, they got their tea in the field. So it was her birthday she they put the scones in, the sixpence in you
 know, and took it out, and she never found the sixpence. She always said her brother had taken it out you know, but he hadn't, she swallowed it you know. Yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your parents ever play games with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Well just playing ball or something in the yard you know, and at night perhaps play dominoes you know, or anything like that, the winter nights you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You said your father always said grace at mealtimes, would you ever have any other sort of family prayers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, not really. No, just grace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you ever taken out by your parents visiting relatives or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, we used to go yes. Of course we were all practically living within a small area you know, easy to get to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And did you ever have any outings further a field with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, there was never holidays in those days. No, no. The only outing we ever had was the Sunday School picnic, we went in farm carts.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Where did you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 To some, just some outlying farms you know, they invited you know, tea party and that was as far as we got.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your parents go or was it only the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your parents went as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes they all went as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 On a Sunday, would you wear your Sunday best?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, if you were going to church, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And did you have to change out of them as soon as you got back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, oh no. Just keep them, yes. Of course you weren't allowed to just romp about after \{ILLEGIBLE\}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of social things did the Chapel organise in those days
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 In those days, well there was very little, apart from the Sunday School, very little else. Of course we hadn't a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 hall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 , then you see, \{ILLEGIBLE\} Hall, so there w
asn't much activity through the week, we were able to do more since we got the hall, well there's always something. And we've just decorated it this year, voluntary labour, four of us did it from top to bottom, kitchens, cloakroom and all. We got an estim
ate from a decorator }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8156036 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 120 and we did it and it cost us nothing ---
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you say that your father was interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Not much no. He didn't bother much with politics. Liberal he was, I knew he was a Liberal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 In some places, men felt that they risked losing their job if they voted one way, did your father think this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
This was a strong Liberal constituency, well 'twas when Sir Edward Grey was at Parliament you see, and he lived at Felton hill Northumberland. And I used to
 drive the agent you see, for Sir Edward Grey and we used to have to go to, if Sir Edward was in London, the agent had to go to pay their wages on the Estate you see, and when I took the agent I used to have a look round the house, you know how it was, it
 
was left open for you, you could go through and have a look round in fact one day I went, and I didn't go round if he was at home. So I went to one of the head woodmen, and they were cleaning out ditches in the wood you know, so I said to the head woodmen
, "Is Sir Edward at home?" "No" he said "There he is" and he was in the ditch, cleaning ditches with them. I nearly dropped! Yes. Fine gentleman he was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
He just looked up and laughed "Go on" he says, "Go on round" The squirrels used to come into the dining room window he had a dish of nuts on the dining room table, you'd see}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14627296  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 the squirrels sitting around that dish, going in and out the window. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Great naturalist. Yes. And he had a pond, that had all the different varieties of ducks on it, lovely sight. Yes. His wife was killed you know in a horse and trap accident.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So your father voted Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about your mother, had she any interest in politics do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, I think she just voted as Father voted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 She did. What would your parents do when their work was over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh they just sat down and, of course at night they were pretty tired after their day's work. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 They never went out in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Not at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well you see to go anywhere you had about four miles to go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
I remember once me father taking me from New Barns, I wasn't very old, there was a Christmas tree at the Presbyterian Church and the snow, you couldn't see the top of the hedges and you could walk on the top of the snow, and he 
carried me on his shoulders to see the Christmas tree, I can always remember that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
The whole thing was one white blanket. You couldn't, there was no mark of fences or anything you know. I can never forget that, I have always remembered that vividly. And of
 course it wouldn't be easy for him you know, carrying me all the way to Warkworth, on the top of the snow. It would be about, 'twas four miles from Brotherwick, two miles from the New Barnes. And then there was none of these houses here then you know. Al
l open fields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you were still a school boy, did you get on, how did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well fairly well. We got through to Standard 7 you know. What we called X-7 you know, that was the finishing class. I was under tw
o schoolmasters. And the first schoolmaster we had, he wasn't just very brisk you know, he didn't give impression, but the second one came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, and he changed all the schooling you know, everything was changed, even handwriting and everything. W
ell you know, he upset the other writing, especially anyone that had been say four or five standards there, and got into that way, and he came at the last, and changed it you see, sort of upset the - I don't think it was a good thing if you had a change o
f schoolmasters in your schooling.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were your friends mostly schoolfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Or were they neighbours children as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Where would you play out mostly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh well, we'd have to come about, perhaps to Warkworth St
ation where you met more children you see, that was the nearest, about ten minutes walk, and there were several children there, and we used to get along there, and they would perhaps come along to the farm. We used to amuse ourselves about the farm you kn
ow. Climbing about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 There weren't any children who your parents wouldn't want you mixing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, no. They were all really nice people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you ever go for walks or fishing or cycling or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 We would go walks, but we
 never did any fishing or cycling, In fact I never had a cycle until I was - oh I was - 40 years of age when I got a cycle. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 
Of course after we did away with the horses, I went into the garage and I had a month's tuition, driving and mechanical work you know.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 That's a lot later on though isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would anybody outside your home ever help your mother at all, apart from your mother's elder sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, the farmer was very good you know, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would happen if your mother was ill or in bed or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well they just had to, some of the elder ones used to have to stick in you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What happened when your younger brothers and sisters were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh they were a great delight, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you warned at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You'd no idea you were expecting a new one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
No, no, no. It was always a surprise, to us. Oh yes, we'd all take a turn of rocking the cradle. Because there was only about two years between each of us you know. We quite \{ILLEGIBLE\} rocking the cradle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did your parents have friends nearby at all who they would go and visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, me father had a brother just lived up at \{ILLEGIBLE\} oh pretty near, within }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 travelling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  distance, yes. Mother had a sister lived in Alnwick, she had a large family too, She used to often come out, so did her children, yes, oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You saw these people pretty frequently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, because you could get the train from Alnwick to Walkworth you know. And if we went, if we had to 
go in for new boots or anything like that, we were taken in by train into Alnwick you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would your mother take you or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, me mother would take us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many of you would go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It would depend - it was too expensive 
for the lot. No, if any of us wanted anything, well was in need of anything, boots or anything, she would take you in to see. Of course the shopping, well the grocer come once a month you know, took the order and would deliver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Not very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Once a month. Mind you, it was generally a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 cargo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  when it came. You see you couldn't afford to go into Alnwick every week and buy just bit by bit, that was the cheapest way to do it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of things would he bring?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh nearly everything you could mention in the grocery line. Stones of sugar you know, not pounds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 People often say that they made their own amusements in those days, would you say this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, well they young people, they used to have dances, some, you'd get thos
e ones was musical you know, they used to dance in the yard. Yes. There was a family lived next to us, young girls and lads you know, about their twenties you know, they used to have dancing out on the road, great step dancers you know. I had a go at it, 
b
ut I couldn't get away with it. Oh yes, you'd get a few in the district like, there were always a few musical, violins and melodion yes. And then we had, after the harvest was in, we had a corn supper. Every year you know. In the granary. Yes. Used to inv
ite the neighbouring farms too you know. Then when they had theirs they invited us. So you got perhaps one or two harvest suppers in the season you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Plenty of good food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Some people say you can split up society into the different social groups would you say that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 That wasn't the case then. No. All equal then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about farmers though, weren't they sort of separate from -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, they were. But they were good to their workers you know, very good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What about the other people, like the parson and the minister and the schoolmaster. Wouldn't you say they were separate from -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, they were yes. Yes. Well we looked upon them as something higher you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did your parents bring you up to treat these people differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes. We had to respect these people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 In what sort of ways would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Well we had to, people with a title or anything like that, you had to Sir them, or Sir the Minister. Very strict on that. Yes. Yes, you had to sort of look up to these people you know because it was your bread and butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Who in fact were \{ILLEGIBLE\} the most important people do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh the church was the main, the minister. And he used to visit regular you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were they different sort of people who went to the Church and the Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, you got the monied people and you got the poor people you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And the people with money normally went to the Church of England did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes. We had, in the Pr
esbyterian Church we had quite a lot of farmers you know, lot of farmers. But you see a lot of farmers had to pay a tithe to the Anglican Church. Oh yes, now the Presbyterians, we subscribed to the Minister's salary you see, we've got to pay for the Minis
ter's salary. But the church at one time, all farmers paid a tithe to the church. What they call a tenth I think, a tenth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was this still in effect in your young days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, it was. Yes, it is not many years ago since that was done away with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So how would the Presbyterian farmers feel about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh, it didn't affect us. You see if they were Presbyterians they didn't pay it. That's why there were perhaps more farmers than the Anglican Church! Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What special group would you say your parents thought they were part of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Well just the usual, they knew everybody, you knew everybody in the village you know, socially. In fact in Warkworth, when I went to school, I could name every person up one side of the street and down the other. Now I couldn't!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When your father moved from being a farm labourer, to being a bailiff, wouldn't this make some sort of difference in your social standing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well no, because we were all married and away you know. We were on our own. And me fathe
r was left, after me mother died, me father was left and me sister kept house for him till he died. So it didn't, he enjoyed his retirement. And we all used to visit him you know. And I remember he came to see me at Eastfield. And when I, we were settling
 down, the missus and I, to Warkworth to catch the bus, he says "Am I walking too fast for you?" and he was 84.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He must have been in very good shape.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, he was. I always say good living helps that you know good living all your life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did your parents have a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well it would be, till some of us got onto work you know, it was a bit of a struggle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Your father wasn't ever out of work though was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Wasn't he ever ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I don't think, I can
 never remember him being laid off with illness. And then during the year, when the stock, you know the sheep at night, well during the lambing times, he had to get up two or three times during the night to look at them. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 He could have had much sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No. Of course that just lasted, perhaps a week or two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 While you were still at school, did you have any part-time jobs which you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, we hadn't, because before you'd walked home you know, four miles, there wasn't much time. 5
 o'clock before you got your tea, nearly six, and it was dark you know, well you couldn't do very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I wondered if you might have worked for the farmer at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, no, we didn't. In fact he didn't, he wouldn't employ below a certain age you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Not even during the summer holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You actually started work when you were 13?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
14. I left school on the Friday night, that was the finish of the schooling, and I went to a farm, neighbouring farm, 6 o'clock in the morning, Monday morning, so that is all the holiday I got between school, and I have worked ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How did you get this job, through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, you see he didn't want, me father didn't want me to start under him you see. He thought better u
nder a stranger you see. And one year, then I come back onto the farm, under me father for one year, then I got this gardeners job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you worked in your first job, Mr. Grey was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Mr. Grey, yes, the one year I was on the farm, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What were you doing in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh general farm work. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 I remember I wasn't very big then you know, and the farmer came into the stable you know, that morning, he says of course he had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ploughman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 /steward you know and he says to me "Take those pair of horses and go to the plough. Well I had never heard of the plough, and couldn't reach up to the horses. So the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 ploughman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 /steward harnessed the horses, put me onto the back and we all went to the field, \{ILLEGIBLE\} plough, now he says "Just come in
 behind me and follow me and I'll keep you right" and that's how I started. He says "You'll never learn younger"
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of hours were you working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 6 till 5. You had an hour off for dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you go home for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, I got it on the farm, yes, the farmer supplied the dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of a meal was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Grand. Plenty of good food. Of course they used to kill their own sheep for mutton you know, chickens. We did have to work overtime harvest I mean, you had to go in and have supper. Oh they were very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What wages were you getting then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I got a shilling a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you work all day Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, half day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was it a fair wage, a shilling a day do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It was at that time, for a start you know. Well you see a farm labourer hadn't, he only had \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 a farm labourer, a full grown person.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you hand over your wage, to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, hand over my wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Had you any spending money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You'd get a few coppers perhaps for your pocket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would you spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh just sweets, down in the village or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of a man was your employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh he was a farmer, gentleman farmer and land agent as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How did he treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Very well. Very well. When I went as groom/gardener, I got all me food in the house. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So you stayed with Mr. Grey for a year and then you worked for your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, for one year, and then went into the farmhouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you worked for your father was it the same sort of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Same sort of work, yes. Whatever seasonal work was on,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did you prefer it working with your father or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well I was never really, I never really fancied the farm work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So you weren't very happy working at the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
No, and the farmer came to me and he said to me would I come along in the morning and clean the boots, do the horse, exercise the horse and he says "I'll give you a job in the garden" so I went, and well he
 never came out till about 11 o'clock to give us a job in the garden, it only lasts about half an hour, the job I had to do. He came back at night he says "Come back in the morning, do the same as you've done, go into the garden and let me see what you ca
n do" and I was there fifteen years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So you go on very well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. I was fifteen years with Mr. Tate. And then I went to \{ILLEGIBLE\} after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of wages were you earning when you started with Mr. Tate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Well I was getting about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8156036 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 2 a week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 And you were still at home in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Sleeping at home, but all me food at the farmhouse you see
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So did you give your mother any of your wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes, yes. Even after I went into the Army you see I gave her an allowance from the Army. So she had that all the four years.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What sort of hours were you working as a groom/gardener?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 About the same about 7 to 5. Of course if you had to go out, sometimes you had to turn out at night, if your people were going
 to a party or anything, sometimes you had to turn out at night you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you paid extra for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, well you took the time off in the morning you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Of course after I went to Sanderson, we had more of that, more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 night work
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 . Young ladies going to dances. Theatres in Newcastle, used to go to Newcastle and pick them up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you started work, would you still help your mother at all in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, you see I had to come home to sleep. Well I brought the milk and then 
in the morning the other saved her carrying, with me walking there you see a sleeping at house. Oh it was a good saving for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 What would you spend your spare time doing, when you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh in the evening, when I was with the Tates, of 
course we had a harness room with a lovely fire you know. And the old gentleman would come round, he wouldn't smoke in the house you know, and he used to come round to the saddle room every night, sit and chat you know, have his pipe. I hadn't, Harness ro
om washed out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Linoleum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  and everything. Just like a house you know. Oh would you had all \{ILLEGIBLE\}
. Even the stables you know. Washed out. \{ILLEGIBEL\}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It sounds as if you enjoyed that sort of work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. Yes. Well I was only seventeen. 
Driving in silk hat and livery! All your livery was made at a firm in Alnwick, Ackroyd, Alnwick, he made all the liveries. You had two suits in a year. Well it was all spit and polish then you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Was he a strict employer do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No, he left you mostly to yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Were you working mostly by yourself or \{ILLEGIBLE\} people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Oh yes, by myself. Well they never interfered. Of course they could see whether you were doing it, to suit them. Of course I was if they wanted anything don
e, I did it their way, if it pleased them, that was all right with me, you see. I was pleasing them. And then they couldn't come back at you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14627296  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
know say "You've done this wrong, you've done that wrong" because you did it to \{ILLEGIBLE\} please them, not yourse
lf. That's where chaps get into trouble over jobs you know, they will try to dictate what should be done. Well whoever's paying the piper can dictate!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 When you were a young man, what sort of a social life had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 A }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 whist drive}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 . Dances I never c
ould get away with. Then we used to have a literary society you know, it was run by the Presbyterian Minister then, you had to prepare a discussion you see. Prepare a paper for discussion, different ones took their turns you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Would you spend evenings out with your friends, or would you spend your evenings at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
At home, yes, yes. Unless there was anything special on. No, the travel was the disadvantage you know, the distance you had to travel to anything you see. No buses. And if you did 
go, you had to go sort of, a few of your friends, as a party you see, for company you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Did you meet any girlfriends when you were at Mr. Tate's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes, yes, yes. Because they had, kept two maids in the house. They had a cook had been 50 y
ears with them. She was like a mother to me. Yes. And I used to, on a Friday or Saturday morning, of course she was getting on in years, and I used to go and wash the back premises out the scullery floor and so on, well you had to work to each other's han
ds you know, see us go in and clean silver, anything like that. Very domesticated!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
It was a lovely neat house too. Plenty of food. This cook, she was great on making spice puddings. You know. And of course if went into the room yo
u know, and it came out, for the staff you see, so one day the cook says, "Here's a spice pudding" she says "Not a bit had been taken off it." She says "We can't afford to waste this \{ILLEGIBLE\}
" she said "You eat one half and I'll eat the other" and we did. So I saw her during the afternoon she said "I wish I hadn't eaten that"! But she didn't believe in, she wouldn't waste nothing. So \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 well if you've any of that left, keep it and fry it up and I will have it for me supper! Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 How many servants were there in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Cook and housemaid. You know. In the house. Now }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 Sanderson's}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296  when I went to Sanderson there was five maids. Of course it was a bigger family. And it was all, there was no electric light then, it was all oil lamps you know. W
e used to burn about 15 gallon of oil a week. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10381199\charrsid14627296 You know it was really a maid's job trimming the lamps. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
Yes. Then we went on to acetylene light \{ILLEGIBLE\} light you know. That place was burnt to the ground you know, after I, just a year or two back. It
 was, the chap that took it over, he ran it as a hotel, and I think someone left a cigarette or something, it was burnt out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 You were there for how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 32 years. Under different landlords. There was Sanderson, Patterson, N.D.Young, and the Great James Duker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 So how old were you when you finished working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 
I would be about, oh 65 when I finished there, then I went to Foxbury 11 years there. I didn't retire till I was seventy. And I've nearly done as much work since I retired. Yo
u see, being so well known in the Warkworth are, anyone has any job to do - they ----
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Enormous. An old country gentleman. \{BLANK\}
 Bridgend House, then St.Lawrence's Terrace you know, comes up the side. That on the left, used to be the old stables, o
h yes. They have made them into four flats. Lovely flats they have made of it. All stables. That was a big establishment at one time. Then we used to have a Mayor of Warkworth you know. Mr. Lamb \{BLANK\} was the Mayor. But that was done away with. \{
BLANK\} And the old Castle, of course it has never changed much. It's much more, it is nicer kept now than it used to be. It used to be growing wild you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Ministry of Works did it up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Yes, they are in charge now you know. Tidied everything up and excavated all the grounds inside the Castle, the foundations are more like 
\{BLANK\} now which they weren't before you see. And they have made a nice lawn and it is kept cut you know. Made a great improvement. Do you know what that makes a year? A thousand a ye
ar. The Castle. For the Ministry of Works. The Custodian told me last year. He said "a thousand a year." I could hardly believe it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Are there many visitors then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 Oh yes. We get a lot of students you know. Bus loads of them. And I once said to th
e Custodian of course he is the right man for the job you know, he can talk like a book you know, and I said "How do you deal with a whole bus load at once?" "Oh" he said "I just tell them anything!" he says. He must get fed up with it. Providing all the 
same history every time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I haven't got the - I used to have a history of Warkworth. It's good, I don't know whether you have ever read it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1930389 JD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 No I haven't seen it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 It's worth having, it is still published, yes. The Post Office used to have it for sale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5850145 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222697\charrsid14627296 I will enquire.
